  "example": {
    "code": "import whest as we\n\ntest = we.array([0, 1, 2, 5, 0])\n\nstates = [0, 2]\n\nmask = we.in1d(test, states)\n\nmask\n\ntest[mask]\n\nmask = we.in1d(test, states, invert=True)\n\nmask\n\ntest[mask]",
    "output": "array([ True, False,  True, False,  True])\n\narray([0, 2, 0])\n\narray([False,  True, False,  True, False])\n\narray([1, 5])",
    "source": "derived"
  },
  "href": "/docs/api/ops/in1d",
  "name": "in1d",
  "next": {
    "href": "/docs/api/ops/indices",
    "label": "we.indices"
  },
  "notes": "Set membership; cost = (n+m)*ceil(log2(n+m)).",
  "notes_sections": [
    "`in1d` can be considered as an element-wise function version of the python keyword `in`, for 1-D sequences. ``in1d(a, b)`` is roughly equivalent to ``we.array([item in b for item in a])``. However, this idea fails if `ar2` is a set, or similar (non-sequence) container:  As ``ar2`` is converted to an array, in those cases ``asarray(ar2)`` is an object array rather than the expected array of contained values.",
    "Using ``kind='table'`` tends to be faster than `kind='sort'` if the following relationship is true: ``log10(len(ar2)) > (log10(max(ar2)-min(ar2)) - 2.27) / 0.927``, but may use greater memory. The default value for `kind` will be automatically selected based only on memory usage, so one may manually set ``kind='table'`` if memory constraints can be relaxed."
  ],
  "numpy_ref": "np.in1d",
  "parameters": [
    {
      "body": [
        "Input array."
      ],
      "name": "ar1",
      "type": "(M,) array_like"
    },
    {
      "body": [
        "The values against which to test each value of `ar1`."
      ],
      "name": "ar2",
      "type": "array_like"
    },
    {
      "body": [
        "If True, the input arrays are both assumed to be unique, which",
        "can speed up the calculation.  Default is False."
      ],
      "name": "assume_unique",
      "type": "bool, optional"
    },
    {
      "body": [
        "If True, the values in the returned array are inverted (that is,",
        "False where an element of `ar1` is in `ar2` and True otherwise).",
        "Default is False. ``we.in1d(a, b, invert=True)`` is equivalent",
        "to (but is faster than) ``we.invert(in1d(a, b))``."
      ],
      "name": "invert",
      "type": "bool, optional"
    },
    {
      "body": [
        "The algorithm to use. This will not affect the final result,",
        "but will affect the speed and memory use. The default, None,",
        "will select automatically based on memory considerations.",
        "",
        "* If 'sort', will use a mergesort-based approach. This will have",
        "  a memory usage of roughly 6 times the sum of the sizes of",
        "  `ar1` and `ar2`, not accounting for size of dtypes.",
        "* If 'table', will use a lookup table approach similar",
        "  to a counting sort. This is only available for boolean and",
        "  integer arrays. This will have a memory usage of the",
        "  size of `ar1` plus the max-min value of `ar2`. `assume_unique`",
        "  has no effect when the 'table' option is used.",
        "* If None, will automatically choose 'table' if",
        "  the required memory allocation is less than or equal to",
        "  6 times the sum of the sizes of `ar1` and `ar2`,",
        "  otherwise will use 'sort'. This is done to not use",
        "  a large amount of memory by default, even though",
        "  'table' may be faster in most cases. If 'table' is chosen,",
        "  `assume_unique` will have no effect."
      ],
      "name": "kind",
      "type": "{None, 'sort', 'table'}, optional"
    }
  ],
